"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_side_effects_glucose_01",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Side effects / Increased fasting blood glucose",
"text": "Atorvastatin has been associated with a small increase in fasting blood glucose levels over a 2-year period, particularly in patients with type 2 Diabetes, however evidence is conflicting and clinical significance of this increase has not been determined."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_side_effects_cognitive_01",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Side effects / Cognitive",
"text": "While rare cases of reversible memory loss and confusion have been reported with statin use, including atorvastatin, multiple systematic review and meta-analyses have found no consistent evidence of a causal relationship."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_interactions_01",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Side effects / Interactions",
"text": "Co-administration of atorvastatin with one of CYP3A4 inhibitors such as itraconazole, telithromycin, and voriconazole, may increase serum concentrations of atorvastatin, which may lead to adverse reactions."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_interactions_02",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Side effects / Interactions",
"text": "This is less likely to happen with other CYP3A4 inhibitors such as diltiazem, erythromycin, fluconazole, ketoconazole, clarithromycin, cyclosporine, protease inhibitors, or verapamil, and only rarely with other CYP3A4 inhibitors, such as amiodarone and aprepitant."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_mechanism_01",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Mechanism of action",
"text": "As with other statins, atorvastatin is a competitive inhibitor of HMG-CoA reductase. Unlike most others, however, it is a completely synthetic compound."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_mechanism_02",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Mechanism of action",
"text": "Inhibition of the enzyme decreases de novo cholesterol synthesis, increasing expression of low-density lipoprotein receptors (LDL receptors) on hepatocytes. This increases LDL uptake by the hepatocytes, decreasing the amount of LDL-cholesterol in the blood."
},
{
"snippet_id": "atorvastatin_mechanism_03",
"source": "[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atorvastatin)",
"section": "Mechanism of action",
"text": "Like other statins, atorvastatin also reduces blood levels of triglycerides and slightly increases levels of HDL-cholesterol."
}
],
